※※
# workflow-forge

A META-workflow that authors another `.sky` workflow from a plain-English intent, then
DRIVES it through sky's OWN tooling as quality gates — `skyway lint` (clean) and
`skyway run --dry-run` (DAG resolves, vars wire, no cycles, budget estimates) — looping
author → lint → lint-fix until the candidate lints clean, then dry-runs it, has opus judge
it against the intent, and only on a fail-CLOSED gate opens a staged PR. It DOGFOODS sky on
sky: the harness builds harness workflows, gated by the harness's own validators.

Intent is supplied at run time:

  skyway run workflow-forge --var intent="a manual workflow that greets the operator and exits"

(Trigger is manual-only; `--var` is the singular flag — the daemon flattens it to {{intent}}
in prompts and $SKY_INTENT in bash. If you read older notes saying `--vars`, the binary's
flag is `--var key=value`, repeatable.)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SAFETY SCOPE (v1) — READ THIS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
The gates are `skyway lint` + `skyway run --dry-run` ONLY. v1 does **NOT** execute the
model-generated `.sky` for real. Running untrusted, model-authored workflow code against a
live daemon (real Claude turns, real bash, real network/PR side effects) is the issue's hard
open question (#314); the safe-exercise sandbox that would let us *run* a generated workflow
under containment is DEFERRED until that sandbox is specified. So v1 proves a candidate is
STRUCTURALLY sound and INTENT-aligned, never that it behaves correctly at runtime. That is
the deliberate v1 boundary — stated here so a future reader does not mistake "delivers" for
"verified-at-runtime".

All mutation happens under `isolation = "worktree"` and lands as a staged PR. The live
checkout is never edited in place; nothing is auto-merged. Per the protected-files boundary
(#39), finalize never auto-commits MISSION.md / FACTORY_RULES.md / .github/ / .sky/
definitions or learnings — CI is the quality gate (the prod container has no Go toolchain),
and a human merges.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
HOW THE GATES RESOLVE THE CANDIDATE (mechanism — important, non-obvious)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
`skyway lint <path>` reads ANY file path directly — easy.
`skyway run --dry-run` does NOT take a path; it resolves a workflow BY NAME, scanning the
current repo's `.sky/workflows/` and matching the `name =` field in ⊕meta⊕ against the run
argument. (Verified: a file placed in `.sky/workflows/` only resolves when its internal
`name =` equals the `skyway run <name>` argument.) So the gates use a deterministic
CANDIDATE-NAME contract:

  - `author` emits ONLY the raw `.sky` body (no fences) whose ⊕meta⊕ carries
    name = "forge-candidate" — a FIXED sentinel name the gate nodes know.
  - `write-candidate` (bash) writes $SKY_OUTPUT_AUTHOR verbatim to BOTH
      <repo>/.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky   (so `skyway run forge-candidate --dry-run` resolves it)
      $RUNTMP/forge-candidate.sky                  (a stable path for lint + later inspection)
    then prints the two paths as a greppable block.
  - `lint` / `dry-run` operate on `forge-candidate`; `cleanup`/`finalize` rename it to the
    REAL intended workflow name only when writing the PR.

The candidate file in `.sky/workflows/` is a TEMP scratch artifact for the dry-run resolver;
it is git-ignored territory under the worktree and is removed by `cleanup`. The forge runs
with cwd = the workflows-internal checkout, so `.sky/workflows/` is the repo tier the
resolver scans.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DAG (v1 — gate on lint + dry-run only; never execute the generated workflow)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (manual run: skyway run workflow-forge --var intent="…")
        │
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  claude (haiku). Classify new-vs-improve; pick trigger + node shape
   │    parse     │  for {{intent}}. Cheap orientation only — emits a short plan.
   └──────────────┘
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  claude (opus). Generate the FULL candidate .sky body. ⊕meta⊕ name MUST
   │    author    │  be "forge-candidate". Output ONLY the file body — no prose, no fences.
   └──────────────┘
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  bash, no LLM. Write $SKY_OUTPUT_AUTHOR to .sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky
   │write-candidate│ + $RUNTMP/forge-candidate.sky. Print both paths.
   └──────────────┘
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  loop (max 3). Each pass: opus REWRITES the whole candidate, re-writing
   │   fix-loop   │  the file, until `skyway lint` exits 0. loop.until.bash is the lint gate;
   └──────────────┘  body context = "fresh" so each fix turn starts clean. First pass = the
        │            initial author output already on disk; the loop self-corrects SKY-WF-*.
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  bash, no LLM. Authoritative lint AFTER the loop: `skyway lint … --format json`.
   │    lint      │  Emit one clean JSON line {"clean":"true|false"} (+ the codes if dirty).
   └──────────────┘
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  bash, no LLM. when clean. `skyway run forge-candidate --dry-run --format json`.
   │   dry-run    │  DAG resolves, vars wire, no cycles, budget estimate. NEVER runs for real.
   └──────────────┘  Emit {"dry_ok":"true|false"}.
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  claude (opus). Does the candidate MATCH {{intent}} (trigger, node shape,
   │    judge     │  behavior on paper)? Ends with EXACTLY one sentinel line:
   └──────────────┘  SKY_FORGE delivers=<true|false>
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  bash, no LLM. FAIL-CLOSED gate: delivers=true ONLY if lint clean AND
   │    gate      │  dry_ok AND the judge sentinel says true. Anything missing/garbled → false.
   └──────────────┘  Emit {"delivers":"true|false"}.
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  claude (opus), isolation = "worktree". when delivers == 'true'. Rename the
   │   finalize   │  candidate to its real name, write it + a manifest.yaml entry, push a branch,
   └──────────────┘  open a PR. Staged, never auto-merged. Protected files untouched.
        │ depends_on
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  bash, no LLM. trigger_rule all_done. Remove the scratch
   │   cleanup    │  .sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky so the repo tier is left clean.
   └──────────────┘

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PR ROUTING (operator decision; v1 default)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
The TARGET repo depends on the workflow's audience:
  - public-meta workflow  → skylence-be/workflows        (end-user `skyway library` source)
  - internal/dogfood      → skylence-be/workflows-internal (this repo)
  - demo/example          → skylence-be/workflow-examples
v1 DEFAULTS to opening the PR against workflows-internal and surfaces the routing call to the
operator in the PR body (the finalize prompt asks for an explicit routing line). Moving a
workflow to the public repo is a deliberate human decision, not an autonomous one.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
BOUNDS & IDEMPOTENCE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Bounded by max_budget_usd = 8.00 and loop.max = 3. Idempotent on an already-passing
workflow: an intent that describes a workflow which is already lint-clean and intent-aligned
flows straight through (fix-loop exits on the first lint pass) and the only side effect is a
PR the operator can close as a no-op.

PREREQUISITES:
  - cwd at run time = the workflows-internal checkout (so `.sky/workflows/` is the repo tier).
  - `gh` authed with repo scope for finalize's PR.
  - `sky` on PATH inside the run environment (the gates shell out to it).

DEVIATIONS from the issue DAG are listed at the bottom of this file's commit message / PR;
the structural shape matches: parse → author → lint → lint-fix(loop) → dry-run → judge →
gate → finalize, with a deterministic write-candidate inserted before lint and a cleanup
after finalize (both bash, no LLM) to manage the candidate scratch file.

Cartographer orientation: OMITTED in v1. The issue makes it optional; adding the
cartographer HTTP MCP + its secret widens the dependency surface of a workflow whose value is
the lint/dry-run/judge loop, not code-graph orientation. A future version may add a
cartographer step (skills = ["cartographer-rules"] + an mcp_servers cartographer-http block,
as in cartographer-reindex.sky) once the safe-exercise sandbox lands.
※※

⊕meta⊕
name = "workflow-forge"
description = "META-workflow: author a target .sky workflow from a plain-English intent, then drive it through sky's own gates — skyway lint (clean) + skyway run --dry-run (DAG/vars/cycles/budget) — looping author→lint→lint-fix until clean, dry-run it (NEVER executed for real in v1), have opus judge it against the intent with a fail-closed gate, and open a STAGED PR under worktree isolation. Uses sky's own lint + dry-run as its gates. Bounded by max_budget_usd + loop.max. Fire via: skyway run workflow-forge --var intent=\"…\""
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 8.00
learnings.exclude = ["anti-patterns"]
ui = "ui/workflow"
⊕⊕

※parse※
Step 1 — parse. Cheap haiku orientation. Classify the intent as new-vs-improve and sketch the
trigger + node shape author should produce. No file IO. {{intent}} is the operator's --var.
※※

§parse§
model = "haiku"
max_turns = 6
ui = "ui/parse"
§§

∆parse∆
You are the planning front-end of a workflow-authoring pipeline. The operator wants a `.sky` workflow. Read their intent and produce a SHORT authoring plan for the next (author) step. Be terse.

INTENT:
{{intent}}

Decide and output, as a compact bullet list:
1. mode: `new` (create a fresh workflow) or `improve` (edit an existing one). If the intent names or describes an existing workflow to change, it is `improve`; otherwise `new`.
2. trigger: exactly one of `trigger.manual = true`, `trigger.github.events = [...]`, `trigger.sky_event.event = "..."`, or `trigger.schedule.cron = "..."` — pick the one the intent implies; default to `trigger.manual = true` when ambiguous.
3. node shape: a short ordered list of the DAG nodes (id + kind: prompt/bash/script/http/loop/cancel/emit/invoke) the workflow needs to satisfy the intent.
4. risks: any obvious lint traps the author must avoid (bareword `when` RHS, an env-secret reference without a `secrets` entry, `{{var}}` inside bash, `chain_from` not in `depends_on`).

Do not write the `.sky` file yet. Output only the plan.
∆∆

※author※
Step 2 — author. Opus generates the FULL candidate .sky body. CRITICAL CONTRACT: the
candidate's ⊕meta⊕ name MUST be exactly "forge-candidate" so the dry-run resolver finds it by
name. Author emits ONLY the raw file body — no markdown fences, no commentary — because the
next node writes its stdout verbatim to disk.
※※

§author§
model = "opus"
depends_on = ["parse"]
max_turns = 30
ui = "ui/author"
§§

∆author∆
You author `.sky` workflow files for the Skylence harness. Produce a COMPLETE, lint-clean `.sky` file that satisfies the operator's intent, following the plan from the parse step.

OPERATOR INTENT:
{{intent}}

PARSE PLAN:
$SKY_OUTPUT_PARSE

`.sky` format rules you MUST follow (the file is validated by `skyway lint`; inventing keys fails it):
- Four delimiter blocks, each opener/closer alone on its line: `⊕meta⊕`…`⊕⊕` (identity + exactly one trigger), `§<id>§`…`§§` (node config), `∆<id>∆`…`∆∆` (Claude prompt body for that node), `※※`…`※※` (discarded doc/comment).
- ⊕meta⊕ requires `name` and `description` and exactly one trigger (`trigger.manual = true` | `trigger.github.events = [...]` | `trigger.sky_event.event = "..."` | `trigger.schedule.cron = "..."`).
- Real node keys only: `model` (sonnet/opus/haiku), `depends_on`, `when`, `bash`, `script`, `http`, `output_format`, `max_turns`, `max_budget_usd`, `isolation = "worktree"`, `chain_from`, `trigger_rule`, `emit`, `cancel`, `loop.until.bash`/`loop.until.eval`/`loop.max`, `invoke.target`/`invoke.vars`, `skills`, `mcp_servers`. There is NO `env.*`, NO `fresh_context`, NO `allowed_tools` key — use node `context = "fresh"` for a clean turn and `skills = [...]` to load skills.
- `when` is FLAT: `"$node.output == 'value'"` or `"$node.output != 'value'"` or a bare boolean — RHS ALWAYS single-quoted; bareword RHS silently never fires.
- `{{var}}` expands ONLY in `∆` prompt bodies and `http.body` (use `{{var|json}}` inside JSON). In `bash`/`script` use `$SKY_OUTPUT_<NODE_ID>` and `$SKY_<UPPER_KEY>`; never `{{var}}`.
- A secret reference of the form dollar-brace env-NAME is allowed ONLY in `mcp_servers` and HTTP url/body/headers, and every NAME must be declared in `secrets = [...]` in ⊕meta⊕. It is rejected anywhere else (prompt/bash/eval).
- `chain_from = "X"` requires "X" in that node's `depends_on`.
- Always shell-quote `$SKY_*` in bash.

HARD OUTPUT CONTRACT:
1. The candidate's ⊕meta⊕ `name` MUST be exactly `forge-candidate`. (Do NOT use the workflow's real future name yet — the gates resolve it by this fixed sentinel name. The real name is chosen later, at PR time.)
2. Output ONLY the raw `.sky` file body. No ``` fences, no leading/trailing prose, no explanation. The very first non-whitespace characters must begin a `※※` doc block or the `⊕meta⊕` opener; the very last line must be a delimiter closer. The next step writes your stdout verbatim to disk and lints it.
∆∆

※write-candidate※
Step 3 — write-candidate. DETERMINISTIC bash, no LLM. Persists the author's output to two
paths: the repo-tier .sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky (so `skyway run forge-candidate
--dry-run` resolves it by name) and a stable $RUNTMP copy. Prints a greppable path block the
downstream gates read. We write the author's WHOLE stdout ($SKY_OUTPUT_AUTHOR) verbatim — no
templating, no shell splicing of model output into commands (that output is untrusted; it
only ever lands in a file, never in an eval/source sink).
※※

§write-candidate§
depends_on = ["author"]
bash_file = "./scripts/write-candidate.sh"
ui = "ui/write-candidate"
§§

※fix-loop※
Step 4 — fix-loop. opus, body context = "fresh" (each fix turn starts from a clean session,
not a chained one). The loop's stop condition is the LINT itself: loop.until.bash runs
`skyway lint` on the repo-tier candidate and exits 0 when clean, stopping the loop. loop.max = 3
caps the spend. On entry the file already holds author's first draft; each turn the model
re-reads the lint diagnostics and REWRITES the whole file in place to clear the specific
SKY-WF-* / SKY-CFG-* codes. We re-author the FULL file (rather than surgical patches) because
opus rewriting the complete artifact is more reliable than diff-mode under the flat-when/loop
constraints — a documented deviation from the issue's "fix the specific codes" phrasing, but
lint-clean is the contract that matters. The model writes the file with its own Write tool;
the prompt forbids touching anything other than the candidate path.
※※

§fix-loop§
model = "opus"
depends_on = ["write-candidate"]
context = "fresh"
max_turns = 20
loop.until.bash = "skyway lint .sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky --format json | grep -q '^\\[\\]$'"
loop.max = 3
ui = "ui/fix-loop"
§§

∆fix-loop∆
The candidate `.sky` file at `.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky` must lint clean. Run the linter, read the diagnostics, and FIX the file until `skyway lint` reports no errors.

Do exactly this:
1. Run: `skyway lint .sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky --format json`
2. If the output is `[]` (empty array — no diagnostics), the file is already clean: STOP, do nothing else.
3. Otherwise, each diagnostic has a `code` (e.g. SKY-WF-040, SKY-WF-055, SKY-WF-047, SKY-WF-060) and a message. Read the file, fix EVERY reported code, and write the corrected `.sky` back to the SAME path `.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky` using your Write/Edit tool.

Common fixes:
- SKY-WF-042 `chain_from` not in `depends_on` → add the chain target to that node's `depends_on`.
- SKY-WF-055 undeclared env-secret reference (dollar-brace env-NAME) → add NAME to `secrets = [...]` in ⊕meta⊕ (or remove the reference).
- SKY-WF-047 bare `{{var}}` in a JSON string in `http.body` → use the unwrapped `{{var|json}}` form.
- SKY-WF-060 `output_format` not valid JSON Schema → fix the schema object.
- SKY-WF-031 bad `when` → quote the RHS: `"$x.output == 'value'"`.
- SKY-WF-037 loop body is http/eval/wait → use a prompt/command/bash body.

Constraints:
- Edit ONLY `.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky`. Do not touch any other file.
- Keep ⊕meta⊕ `name` exactly `forge-candidate`.
- Do not weaken the workflow's intent to satisfy the linter — fix the FORMAT, preserve the BEHAVIOR.

Output a one-line summary of what you changed (or `already-clean`).
∆∆

※lint※
Step 5 — lint. DETERMINISTIC bash, no LLM. The AUTHORITATIVE lint AFTER the loop (the loop's
own lint is just its stop condition; this node is what the gate trusts). `skyway lint … --format
json` prints `[]` when clean, else a JSON array of diagnostics. We emit ONE clean JSON line
`{"clean":"true|false"}` so the downstream `when` always parses, plus the raw codes to stderr
for the run log. FAIL-CLOSED: only an explicit empty `[]` yields clean=true.
※※

§lint§
depends_on = ["fix-loop"]
bash_file = "./scripts/lint.sh"
ui = "ui/lint"
§§

※dry-run※
Step 6 — dry-run. DETERMINISTIC bash, no LLM. Runs ONLY when lint is clean. `skyway run
forge-candidate --dry-run --format json` renders each node's prompt and resolves the DAG, var
wiring, cycle check, and budget estimate WITHOUT invoking Claude or executing any bash — this
is the v1 safety boundary (we validate structure, we never run the generated workflow for
real). The dry-run resolves the candidate BY NAME from the repo-tier .sky/workflows/. Exit 0 +
non-empty JSON array → dry_ok=true. Emit ONE clean JSON line `{"dry_ok":"true|false"}`.
※※

§dry-run§
depends_on = ["lint"]
when = "$lint.output.clean == 'true'"
bash_file = "./scripts/dry-run.sh"
ui = "ui/dry-run"
§§

※judge※
Step 7 — judge. Opus reads the intent and the actual candidate file and decides whether the
candidate MATCHES the intent (right trigger, right node shape, plausible behavior on paper).
output_format is advisory only — opus often returns prose instead of JSON, so we do NOT gate
on it; instead judge MUST end with EXACTLY one machine sentinel line that the deterministic
gate node greps:  SKY_FORGE delivers=<true|false>
This is the same AI-judge → bash-gate-greps-sentinel pattern as track-anthropic-changes.
※※

§judge§
model = "opus"
depends_on = ["dry-run"]
max_turns = 12
output_format = {"type": "object", "properties": {"delivers": {"type": "boolean"}, "reason": {"type": "string"}}, "required": ["delivers", "reason"]}
ui = "ui/judge"
§§

∆judge∆
You are the acceptance judge for an authored `.sky` workflow. Decide whether the candidate MATCHES the operator's intent. You judge STRUCTURE and INTENT-ALIGNMENT on paper only — the workflow has NOT been executed for real (v1 gates are lint + dry-run only).

OPERATOR INTENT:
{{intent}}

The candidate already passed `skyway lint` (clean) and `skyway run --dry-run` (DAG resolves, vars wire, no cycles). Read the candidate file at `.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky` and assess:
1. Trigger — does the candidate's single trigger match what the intent implies?
2. Node shape — do the DAG nodes (their kinds and dependencies) plausibly accomplish the intent?
3. Behavior on paper — reading each node's prompt/bash/config, would this workflow do what the operator asked? Flag anything that lints clean but is intent-wrong (e.g. a `when` that will never fire, a node that no-ops, a trigger that subscribes to the wrong event).
4. Completeness — is anything the intent asked for missing?

`delivers` is true ONLY if the trigger, node shape, and on-paper behavior all match the intent with nothing material missing. When in doubt, `delivers=false` (a false negative costs another loop; a false positive ships a broken workflow).

Output:
- A short assessment (a few bullet points: what matches, what is off).
- Then, as the VERY LAST line of your output, print EXACTLY this machine sentinel (a downstream bash node parses it — it must be the final line, lowercase true/false, no markdown, no trailing text):
  SKY_FORGE delivers=true
  (or `SKY_FORGE delivers=false`). Do not add any prose after this line.
∆∆

※gate※
Step 8 — gate. DETERMINISTIC bash, no LLM. The FAIL-CLOSED acceptance gate. delivers=true ONLY
when ALL THREE hold: lint clean ($SKY_OUTPUT_LINT), dry_ok ($SKY_OUTPUT_DRY_RUN), and the judge
sentinel says true ($SKY_OUTPUT_JUDGE). A missing/garbled sentinel, a skipped dry-run, or a
dirty lint all yield delivers=false — because a false "delivers" ships a broken workflow as a
PR (the opposite fail-direction from track-anthropic-changes, which fails OPEN because a
spurious issue is cheap; here a spurious PR of broken generated code is NOT cheap). Emit ONE
clean JSON line `{"delivers":"true|false"}`.
※※

§gate§
depends_on = ["lint", "dry-run", "judge"]
trigger_rule = "all_done"
bash_file = "./scripts/gate.sh"
ui = "ui/gate"
§§

※finalize※
Step 9 — finalize. Opus under isolation = "worktree" (per-node throwaway git worktree — the
live checkout is NEVER edited in place). Runs ONLY when the gate says delivers == 'true'.
Renames the candidate from the sentinel name forge-candidate to its REAL intended name, writes
it to the routed repo path, adds a manifest.yaml entry, and opens a STAGED PR (never
auto-merged). PROTECTED-FILES BOUNDARY (#39): never auto-commit MISSION.md / FACTORY_RULES.md /
.github/ / .sky/ definitions or learnings. CI is the quality gate (the prod container has no Go
toolchain). v1 ROUTING DEFAULT: open the PR against this repo (workflows-internal) and put an
explicit routing recommendation in the PR body for the operator to redirect to
skylence-be/workflows (public-meta) or workflow-examples (demo) if appropriate.
※※

§finalize§
model = "opus"
depends_on = ["gate"]
when = "$gate.output.delivers == 'true'"
isolation = "worktree"
max_turns = 40
max_budget_usd = 3.00
ui = "ui/finalize"
§§

∆finalize∆
The candidate workflow passed every v1 gate (lint clean, dry-run clean, judge delivers=true). Ship it as a STAGED pull request. You are in an isolated git worktree — work only here; never push to a base branch and never auto-merge.

OPERATOR INTENT:
{{intent}}

The validated candidate is at `.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky`. Its ⊕meta⊕ `name` is the sentinel `forge-candidate` — you must rename it to the workflow's REAL name now.

Do exactly this:
1. Pick the REAL workflow name: a kebab-case name derived from the intent (e.g. `greet-operator`). The file's ⊕meta⊕ `name =` MUST equal the new filename stem.
2. Decide the routing and target repo. The rule:
   - public-meta workflow (end users would want it via `skyway library`) → skylence-be/workflows
   - internal dogfood/self-improvement → skylence-be/workflows-internal (THIS repo)
   - demo/example → skylence-be/workflow-examples
   v1 default: open the PR against THIS repo (workflows-internal). State your routing recommendation explicitly in the PR body so the operator can move it if the audience is really public/demo.
3. Within this repo, write the renamed file to `production/workflows/<real-name>.sky` (the production tier; mirror the sibling workflows). Update its ⊕meta⊕ `name` and (if present) the candidate's internal sentinel references to the real name. Do NOT leave the `forge-candidate` name in the shipped file.
4. Add a `manifest.yaml` entry mirroring the existing production entries — `kind: workflow`, `path: production/workflows/<real-name>.sky`, `name: <real-name>`, a `description` ending with the fire-command, and `tags` including `tier:production` and `internal`.
5. Do NOT modify, stage, or commit any of: MISSION.md, FACTORY_RULES.md, anything under .github/, any `.sky/` workflow/command/learning definition, or the scratch `.sky/workflows/forge-candidate.sky`. Touch ONLY the new `production/workflows/<real-name>.sky` and `manifest.yaml`.
6. Create a branch, commit the two files, push, and open a PR with `gh pr create`. The PR body must include: the operator intent, the routing recommendation (target-repo decision), and a note that this is a v1 forge output gated by lint + dry-run ONLY (NOT runtime-verified — the generated workflow was never executed for real). Never merge; leave it for human review (CI is the gate).
7. Print the PR URL.
∆∆

※cleanup※
Step 10 — cleanup. DETERMINISTIC bash, no LLM. trigger_rule = "all_done" so it runs whether
finalize ran, was skipped, or failed. Removes the scratch repo-tier candidate file so the
.sky/workflows/ tier is left exactly as found (the candidate was only ever a temp resolution
artifact for the dry-run). Best-effort: a missing file is fine.
※※

§cleanup§
depends_on = ["gate", "finalize"]
trigger_rule = "all_done"
bash_file = "./scripts/cleanup.sh"
ui = "ui/cleanup"
§§
